SIMPLE: marmot
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: marmot
<hw>mar"mot</hw> <pr>(m⟦aum⟧r"m⟦ocr⟧t; 277)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>
<ety>[It. <ets>marmotta</ets>, <ets>marmotto</ets>, prob. fr. L.
<ets>mus montanus</ets>, or <ets>mus montis</ets>, lit., mountain mouse
or rat. See <er>Mountain</er>, and <er>Mouse</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Any rodent of the genus <gen>Marmota</gen>
(formerly <gen>Arctomys</gen>) of the subfamily
<subfam>Sciurinae</subfam>. The common European marmot (<spn>Marmota
marmotta</spn>) is about the size of a rabbit, and inhabits the higher
regions of the Alps and Pyrenees. The <stype>bobac</stype> is another
European species. The common American species (<spn>Marmota monax</spn>)
is the <stype>woodchuck</stype> (also called <stype>groundhog</stype>),
but the name <ex>marmot</ex> is usually used only for the western
variety.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Any one of several species of ground squirrels or
gophers of the genus <gen>Spermophilus</gen>; also, the prairie
dog.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Marmot squirrel</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>a
ground squirrel or spermophile.</cd> -- <col><b>Prairie
marmot</b></col>. <cd>See <er>Prairie dog</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Marmottes oil</ent>⟦br⟧
